@node Intro "Introduction"

@{b}Introduction :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
This program allows to create indexes of reduced  pictures.  It  offers  many
possibilities  and  has  some  features that other programs of this type have
not... And it's totally free !

If you own a great number of  pictures,  this  program  will  become  a  MUST
quickly !

Collector 3.5 is CREATION-WARE.  It's  not  shareware,  like  all  the  other
thumbnails  indexes  creators  in  the  PD,  because  I  wanted  to  bring  a
disinterested contribution to the AMIGA community. So I don't ask a penny for
this  program.  On the other hand, if you have created anything for the AMIGA
(a program, a  music  module  or  a  picture,  or  anything  else),  I  would
appreciate  you  send  me a copy. Let's say it's an exchange of creativity...
(for the SHAREWARE programs, please send me a registered version).
If you want to include Collector in a  CD-ROM  or  a  disk  provided  with  a
magazine, please send me the concerned issue.

Consider that a program like Collector requires really a lot of work, and the
fact  I  offer  it  to you deserves a small gift in exchange... If you really
didn't produce anything on AMIGA (what a shame ! ;-)), send  me  at  least  a
little  mail to tell me what you think of Collector.

For my address, see @{"Author" link Author}. Thanks.

@{b} Please note that any translation for Collector  (catalogs,  docs...)  in
your native language is always welcome ! :-)@{ub}

@endnode

@node Features "Features"

@{b}Features :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~
    - Fast (optimised for 68020+ processors).
    - Compact.
    - Doesn't use MUI, BGUI, Triton,  ClassAct or any other GUI interface.
Only system's Gadtools.library, which seems really sufficient (and much more
memory saving)...
    - Allows creation of 16 or 256 grayscale, or 256 colors thumbnails, with
high image quality.
    - 68000 CPU and ECS modes supported.
    - Supports XPK compression.
    - Respects totally the AMIGA system.
    - Customizable.
    - Handles multi-volumes indexes.
    - Capability to update indexes very easily (all is automatic).
    - Very powerful system of actions associated to each picture format.
    - Customizable popup menus.
    - Can also rename/move/delete pictures on disk.
    - Very flexible thanks to the use of datatypes (you can even catalog your
fonts with the font.datatype, for example !)
    - Can export the indexes into various formats (including HTML !).
    - Free !
@endnode

@node Require "Required configuration"

@{b}Requirements :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
You need system 3.0 or above to use Collector, because it uses datatypes, and
the  AGA  chipsets for 256 colors displays. 16 greyscales display should work
on ECS machines.

Some memory will be also welcome (4 Mb of FAST RAM should  be  sufficient  in
most cases, for a comfortable usage).

Collector 3.5 uses also the MPImage.library (version 8.2  or  above  !),  the
Reqtools.Library and the PopupMenu.Library (version 7 or above) (all provided
in the archive). For the MPImage.library, I strongly encourage you to get the
complete  distribution (on Aminet or at a PD distributor) because it contains
optimised versions  for  each  processor  (and  math  coprocessor).  The  one
provided with Collector is the 68000 version... On Aminet, you can find it in
the gfx/conv/ directory, or get the latest version on the dedicated web  page
at http://www.topic.demon.co.uk.

By the way, the MPImage.library seems to be discontinued. Since it's released
under  the  GNU  licence,  anyone interested in making a PPC version would be
very welcome !

To export pictures in PNG format, you'll need the program PNMTOPNG (available
on Aminet) in your C: directory.
In the same way, to export pictures in JPEG format, you'll need the program
CJPEG (also available on Aminet) in your C: directory.

@endnode

@node Install "Installation"

@{b}Installation :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Very simple !! Simply double-click on the installer script icon. The script
will do the following operations :

    - Copy the MPImage.library, the Reqtools.library and the PopupMenu.library in
your LIBS: directory.

    - Copy the COLLECTOR directory and the files it contains into a directory
you will have chosen before.

    - Check your CPU and install either the 68000 or the 68020 version of the
executable.

    That's all !

    If you own the programs CJPEG, DJPEG, PNMTOPNG and/or PNGTOPNM, you should
copy them to your C: directory (CJPEG  is  necessary  for  JPEG  export,  and
PNMTOPNG for PNG export).

@endnode

@node Running "Running Collector"

@{b}Running Collector :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

You can run Collector :

- from the WorkBench, by simply double-clicking on its icon,

- or from the CLI. You can provide an index name to load as an argument (for
example, type "collector FILE=Gfx:Index/Landscapes.Idx" to run Collector and
load the "Landscapes.Idx" file). You can also specify a priority for
Collector, with the PRIORITY argument, like this : "Collector PRIORITY=-1".

Collector needs to be run from its directory to find important data files. So
don't forget to type "cd <your collector directory>" before launching it from
the CLI.


@{b}VERY IMPORTANT NOTE :@{ub} Collector needs a stack of at least 8192 bytes
to  run  correctly. So if you change the Collector icons, don't forget to put
the value 8192 in the stack gadget of the new icons. In the same way, if  you
run  Collector from the CLI, please be sure that the current process stack is
8192 or above (you can change it with the "stack 8192" command).

@endnode

