@node panneau_reduc "Thumbnails panel"

@{b}Actions on thumbnails :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
- If you click on a thumbnail, it will be selected. Click on it again and  it
will be unselected.

- If you double-click on a thumbnail, the action associated  to  the  picture
format  will  be  executed  (see  @{"Preferences"  link  Prefs}  for  actions definition...).
The most of the time, the picture will be visualised.

- If you click on a thumbnail name, various informations about the original
picture will be displayed (see @{"Picture Info" link InfoImage}).
@endnode

@node panneau_cont "Control panel"

@{b}Actions with the control panel :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
The control panel, at the bottom of the screen, is very simple to use.
Let's see the different buttons :

    - |< and >| : Go to the start / end of your index.

    - « and » : Go to the previous / next page of your index.

    - < and > : Go to the previous / next line of your index.

If you are at the top (resp. bottom) of  a  multi-volumed  index,  and  click
again  on  a button to go up (resp. down) into the index, then Collector will
offer you to load the previous (resp. next) part of the index...

You can also use the horizontal scroll bar for more intuitive moves  in  your
index...

@endnode

@node clavier "Keyboard"

@{b}Keyboard actions :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
- Most of the menu actions have a keyboard shortcut.

- Press Up and Down arrow keys (or Right and Left) to go to the  previous  or
next line.

- Press Shift + Up and Down arrow keys (or Right  and  Left)  to  go  to  the
previous or next page.

- Press Ctrl + Up and Down arrow keys (or Right and Left) to go to the top or
bottom of your index.

If you are at the top (resp. bottom) of  a  multi-volumed  index,  and  press
again  an arrow key to go up (resp. down) into the index, then Collector will
offer you to load the previous (resp. next) part of the index...

- All the moves in the index can also be done with the keys  of  the  numeric
pad.

- Press Help to see the Collector documentation (the Amigaguide program  must
be in the SYS:Utilities directory, which is its usual location...).

@endnode


@node New "New"

@{b}New :@{ub}
~~~~~
This command erases the current index from memory.

If the current index has been modified since the last  save,  Collector  will
ask you if you want to save it first...

@endnode

@node Open "Open"

@{b}Open :@{ub}
~~~~~~
Allows to load a previously saved index into memory...

Sorry, but the indexes created with the very first version of Collector (1.x)
are  not  compatible  with  this version. That's why I coded a converter that
converts 1.x Collector indexes into 2.x format (see @{"Hints and  tips" link Hints}).

If the current index has been modified since the last  save,  Collector  will
ask you if you want to save it first...

@endnode

@node Append "Append"

@{b}Append :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~
Allows to append a Collector index at the end of the current one...

If the  number  of  thumbnails  exceeds  the  maximum  number  of  authorized
thumbnails, then Collector will ask you if you want to continue by truncating
the added index, or cancel the operation.

@endnode

@node Save "Save"

@{b}Save / Save as :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Allows to save the current index on disk.

If you use "Save as", Collector will ask you to specify an index  name.  It's
then  better  to  end this name with the ".Idx" suffix. If you don't do that,
this suffix will be added automatically at the end of the name...

Moreover, Collector keeps at any time  a  list  of  files  that  couldn't  be
eventually  added  to  the index (unknown picture format, unrecognized packed
file, etc...). When you save an index, the list of these faulty files will be
saved in a text file with the same name, but with the ".Flt" suffix.

@endnode

@node Save_sel "Save selected"

@{b}Save selected only / Save selected only as :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Allows to save the currently @{b}selected@{ub} thumbnails into an index.

If you use "Save selected only as", Collector will ask you to specify an
index name. It's then better to end this name with the ".Idx" suffix. If you
don't do that, this suffix will be added automatically at the end of the
name...

Moreover, Collector keeps at any time  a  list  of  files  that  couldn't  be
eventually  added  to  the index (unknown picture format, unrecognized packed
file, etc...). When you save an index, the list of these faulty files will be
saved in a text file with the same name, but with the ".Flt" suffix.

@endnode

@node Complete "Complete"

@{b}Complete :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~
Works like the @{"Add" link Add} function, but only the files  that  are  not
already  in  the current index will be added. This allows to keep an index up
to date, without having to check which pictures were  already  included,  and
which pictures you have to add...

If you use it on  a  single-volumed  index,  this  on  will  be  scanned  for
determining the already included pictures, and those to add.

The same method is used for a multi-volumed index, but here all  the  volumes
of the index are scanned...

@endnode

@node Completeauto "Complete automatically"

@{b}Complete automatically :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Works like the @{"Complete" link Complete} function, but here you don't even have to select
files for completion. Collector scans the current index (and  all  the  other
volumes  if it's a multi-volumed index) and makes a list of all the different
directories involved in the index. Then ALL  the  files  that  are  in  these
directories  and  are  not  already  in the current index will be added. This
allows to keep an index up to date, without having to  check  which  pictures
were already included, and which pictures you have to add...

Please note that this kind of completion could involve many files, especially
if you have directories containing many pictures...

@endnode

@node UpdateIndexFiles "Update index files"

@{b}Update index files :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
This is the ultimate index handling function ! ;-)

Indeed, if you have a great number of indexes, it can be tedious to load each
of them separately, complete them, update them, sort them then save them...

So with this option, you select the indexes you want to update (you can  also
enter a file pattern in the file requester, and all the subdirectories of the
current directory will also be scanned recursively, to collect all the  files
matching  this  pattern),  and for each selected index, Collector will do the
following :

Load
Update index
Complete automatically
Sort
Save

If the sort method is set to "None", the indexes won't be sorted...

@endnode

@node Update_Index "Update"

@{b}Update :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~
Updating an index allows to eliminate all the thumbnails whose references are
obsolete (file deleted, moved, renamed...).

If some files were modified since they were included in the index,  Collector
will offer you to re-create their thumbnails.

If some thumbnails are duplicated, it will offer  you  to  remove  the  extra
entries.

For multi-volumed indexes, only the volume in memory is updated. So to update
completely  a multi-volumed index, you'll have to load and update each volume
independently... (but see {@"Update Index Files" link UpdateIndexFiles} if you want to update
several indexes at once).

@endnode

@node Info "Info"

@{b}Info :@{ub}
~~~~~~
Displays various data about Collector and the system state (available memory,
name  of  the  current index, number of thumbnails in this index, name of the
Collector public screen...)

@endnode

@node Quit "Quit"

@{b}Quit :@{ub}
~~~~~~
Allows to quit Collector...

If the current index has been modified since the last  save,  Collector  will
ask you if you want to save it first...

@endnode


@node Add "Add"

@{b}Add :@{ub}
~~~~~
This function allows you to add one or more thumbnails to your index. To  add
a  picture, you just have to click on it in the file selector, and that's
all !


    For many pictures, you have different possibilities :

- You can use multiselection in the file selector (by clicking on the names
of the files while pressing the shift key), or by clicking on the "Pattern"
gadget and entering a pattern corresponding to the desired files...

- Or you can enter a pattern in the string gadget  where  the  file  name  is
typed.  Thus,  if  you  enter "#?.Gif" (without the quotes), all the pictures
whose name ends by ".Gif" will be added to the index. In this case, Collector
will  ask  you  if you want to also scan sub-directories recursively : if you
answer "Yes", all the files in the  sub-directories  of  this  directory  and
ending by ".Gif" will also be added.


You may want to create an index containing a lot of  pictures  (indeed,  some
CD-ROMs  contain  a  great number of pictures in the same directory). You can
then fragment an index which would be enormous into several  smaller  indexes
(also  called  "volumes")  by  defining  a maximum number of thumbnails in an
index (see @{"Preferences" link Prefs}).

When the number of thumbnails  go  over  the  maximum  number  of  thumbnails
allowed, two cases can be encountered :

- If the current index is single-volumed, Collector will ask you to  enter  a
basename  for  the  different  parts  of  the  index  (which then will become
multi-volumed).

An example : You have 100 thumbnails in the index "Test.Idx". You want to add
300  new  thumbnails to it. And you have set the maximum number of thumbnails
per index to 250. This limit will then be exceeded. Collector will ask you  a
basename  for  the different parts of the index. If you enter "Test" (without
the quotes), Collector will fill the current index to the maximum (250), then
it  will  save it under the name "Test1.Idx". Then it will create a new index
named "Test2.Idx", and it will add the rest of the thumbnails (150).

Therefore you'll have an index in 2 volumes.


- If  on  the  other  hand,  the  current  index  is  already  a  part  of  a
multi-volumed  index,  Collector  will  search the first volume where there's
room left, and add as many thumbnails as possible to it. The same thing  with
all  the  other volumes. Then, if some thumbnails remain to be added, and all
the existing volumes are already full, it will create new volumes...

@endnode

@node Delete "Delete"

@{b}Delete :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~
Erases all the selected thumbnails from the current index...

If you click the "Also on disk" button, the file(s) will also be  deleted  on
the disk ! So be careful not to delete precious files !

@endnode

@node Rename "Rename"

@{b}Rename :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~
Allows to rename all the selected thumbnails...

Useful when you have changed the name of a picture, since you can update  its
name in the index without having to recreate its thumbnail...

If you click the "Also on disk" button, the file(s) will also be renamed  (or
even moved if you change its (their) path) on the disk.

@endnode

@node ChangeDir "Change directory"

@{b}Change directory :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Very useful function ! It  changes  the  access  path  of  all  the  selected
pictures.  Now,  you  can  move  your  pictures  where you want on your disk,
without having to re-create your index at each time !

For  example,  you  have  created  an  index  with  pictures  stored  in  the
"Gfx:Images/LandScapes"  directory. But you decided to move this directory on
your "System:" directory... Normally, you would have  to  re-create  entirely
your  index,  since  all  images  references  are  now obsolete. Fortunately,
there's another solution :

Select all the thumbnails (with the @{"Select all" link Select} function  and
choose "Change directory" in the menu. Then enter "System:Images/LandScapes",
and all the pictures will be renamed with the new directory !!

If you click the "Also on disk" button, the file(s) will also be moved on the
disk  (you should check if there's enough room on destination device to store
all the selected files first).

@endnode

@node Sort "Sort"

@{b}Sort :@{ub}
~~~~~~
Allows to sort the current index following various criteria (name, path, size
and date)...

To set the sort criterion, use the "Sort method" item of the settings menu.
If the criterion is set to "None", then Collector will propose to set it via
a requester when you select this function...

@endnode

@node Select "Selections"

@{b}NOTE : all these actions will only be available if the multi-selection is
activated...


Select all :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~
Selects all the thumbnails in the current index...


@{b}Unselect all :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Unselects all the thumbnails in the current index...


@{b}Select pattern :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Selects all the thumbnails whose name corresponds to a given pattern.

Therefore, if you enter the pattern "#?.Gif", (without the quotes),  all  the
thumbnails whose name ends with ".Gif" will be selected...


@{b}Select range :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
This function selects all the thumbnails  between  the  first  and  the  last
selected thumbnails.

Example : You want to select thumbnails from 1 to 100. Click on the first and
the  100th  thumbnail.  Then  choose  "Select  range"  and all the thumbnails
between 1 and 100 will be selected.


@{b}Toggle selection :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
This function inverses the current selection.

@endnode

@node ExportSelected "Export Selected"

@{b}Export Selected :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
This function allows you to save all the selected  thumbnails  as  individual
pictures files.

When you use it, a file requester will allow you to  select  the  destination
directory where all the files will be saved... Then you'll have to choose the
format of the pictures (currently IFF, JPEG, PNG and PPM are supported).

Note : You'll need the CJPEG program for exporting  JPEG,  and  PNMTOPNG  for
exporting PNG.

@endnode

@node ExportPanels "Export selected as panels"

@{b}Export selected as panels :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
This function allows you to save  all  the  selected  thumbnails  as  graphic
panels, so you can show your indexes even to people not using Collector.

When you use it, a file requester will allow you to  select  the  destination
directory  where  the  pictures  file(s)  will be saved... You can choose the
width and height of the generated panels with the "Exported panels size" item
of the settings menu.

Then you'll have to select the format used to save the panels (currently IFF,
JPEG, PNG, PPM and HTML are supported).
Note : You'll need the CJPEG program for exporting  JPEG,  and  PNMTOPNG  for
exporting PNG.

For HTML Export, Collector will create HTML  pages  containing  the  selected
thumbnails  (converted  to  JPEG).  It  can also create links to the original
(big) pictures. You will be asked if you want to copy the  original  pictures
along with the HTML page : if you answer "Yes", Collector will copy the files
in the "Pics" directory, and the links of the  HTML  page(s)  will  point  to
these  files (useful if you want to create your web site using Collector). If
you answer "No", the original files won't be copied, and the HTML links  will
point to the original location of the pictures on the disk.

If all the selected thumbnails don't fit into a single panel, several panels
will be generated, with a different number added at the end of their name.
For example, if you enter "Landscapes" in the file requester, select "IFF"
export format, and several panels are generated, then they will be named
"Landscapes_001.IFF", "Landscapes_002.IFF", and so on...

@endnode

@node InfoImage "Picture info"

@{b}Picture info :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
This function displays data on  selected  thumbnails.  If  the  size  or  the
comment  of  a  file  have  changed since the archiving date, it will also be
indicated (but the file must be of course accessible to use this feature)
(see @{"Update info" link UpdateInfo}).

@endnode

@node UpdateInfo "Update info"

@{b}Update info :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~
If you modify the size of a picture, or its comment, this command will  allow
you to update these data in your index.

Indeed,  when  you  select  this  command,  all  the  selected  pictures  are
re-examined,  and  if  their  size, their comment or their creation date have
changed, these data will be updated.

@endnode

@node SetComment "Set Comment"

@{b}Set Comment :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~
This function allows to modify the comment associated to a picture (i.e. the
file comment itself) directly from Collector.

@endnode

@node View "Viewing"

@{b}View selected :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Acts as if you'd double-click on all the @{b}selected@{ub} thumbnails, one  after  the
other.


@{b}View all :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~
Acts as if you'd double-click on @{b}all@{ub} the thumbnails of your index, one  after
the other.

@endnode

@node DefineActions "Define actions"

@{b}Define Actions :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Defines the actions associated to each picture type.

Indeed, Collector offers a  very  powerful  actions  system.  Normally,  this
system will be used to visualise pictures, but can be extended to all you can
imagine.

A picture type is  identified  by  its  name.  Thus,  Gif  pictures  will  be
recognized, for example, by the suffix ".Gif" in their name.

You can then tell to Collector to launch the pictures  viewer  FastView  when
you double-click on a picture whose name ends with ".Gif", with the following
action :

                #?.GIF = DH1:TOOLS/VIEW/FASTVIEW "%s" NBMI

@{b}"%s"@{ub} will be replaced by the picture name when executing the action.
Here are some other examples :

                #?.PCX = DH1:TOOLS/VIEW/FASTVIEW "%s" NBMI
                (#?.JPG|#?.JPEG) = DH1:TOOLS/VIEW/FJPEG_AGA "%s" DIRTY NOBUSY
                #? = C:VIEWTEK "%s"

Collector  will  stop  to  the  first  action  corresponding  to  the   right
conditions,  and  won't try to find any other action further in the list that
could be executed too.

If no action corresponds to the thumbnail name, Collector will do nothing...

NOTE : The Collector screen is public, and is called COLLECTOR.x, where x  is
the copy number of Collector in memory. This means you can run several copies
of Collector at the same time : the first  copy  will  use  a  screen  called
COLLECTOR.1, the second one a screen called COLLECTOR.2, and so on (check the
@{"Info " link Info} function to know the name of the used public screen).

So you can display pictures in a window on this screen, provided your  viewer
allows  it  (with  Multiview,  for  example,  with  the PUBSCREEN=COLLECTOR.1
argument (the results won't be very satisfying though, it's better to open  a
separate screen)).


As you can see, nothing prevents you from doing something else than viewing a
picture.  You  could  launch  an Arexx script instead, interfaced with ADPro,
which would process the selected picture (don't forget that  with  the  "View
selected"  and  "View  all" commands, you can automate a process on an entire
index, if you want)... Therefore Collector becomes a real  graphic  interface
for a large number of operations on your pictures.

@endnode

@node DefinePopup "Define popup menu"

@{b}Define popup menu :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Defines the menu items of the popup menu.

Indeed, when you right click on a thumbnail, a popup menu  appears,  and  you
can  apply  an  action to this thumbnail (like printing the original picture,
for example).

The way actions are defined is similar to  the  definition  of  actions  when
double-clicking  a  thumbnail (see @{"Define actions" link DefineActions}).
Thus you can associate an action to every item of the popup menu.

The format of the action is :

                 <NAME> = <ACTION>

For example :
                View = DH1:TOOLS/VIEW/FASTVIEW "%s" NBMI

Then, the "View" item will be added to the popup menu, and when you'll select
it, the Fastview program will be launched. The "%s" symbol will be replaced
by the name of the picture.

This feature allows to define almost any  operation  you  want  to  apply  on
thumbnails.

@endnode


@node Prefs "Preferences"

@{b}Settings menu :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    @{b}Multi-Selection :@{ub}

Allows to select many  thumbnails  at  the  same  time.  If  this  option  is
deactivated,  only  one  thumbnail  can  be  selected  at a time, and all the
selection actions in the "Thumbnails" menu won't be available.


    @{b}Vertical Display :@{ub}

If this option is activated, the thumbnails will be  displayed  from  top  to
bottom instead of left to right.


    @{b}Tight Display :@{ub}

Allows to display a maximum number of  thumbnails  on  the  screen.  It  will
remove  the control panel (but you can still move in the index with the arrow
keys (see @{"Keyboard" link clavier}).


    @{b}Save Icon :@{ub}

When this option is activated, an icon will be saved with your indexes. So if
you double-click on an index icon later, Collector will be run, and the index
will be automatically loaded.

WARNING ! As the default tool in the indexes icons is  "Collector:Collector",
you  must  make  an assign if you want to load an index via its icon. To make
this assign, type in the shell :

                assign Collector: <your collector directory>

(you should add this command in your user-startup; I didn't it myself in  the
installer  script, because I hate all these assigns that programs put in your
user-startup. I prefer do it myself if I decide to keep the  program,  and  I
generally use an assign manager instead, like MCP).


    @{b}Keep proportions :@{ub}

Allows to create the thumbnails while keeping the picture  proportions  (this
was  the  default  mode in previous versions of Collector). If this option is
deactivated, the thumbnails will always fit the whole thumbnails frames.


    @{b}Quick scale :@{ub}

This option uses a new  feature  of  the  MPImage.library  (version  8.2  and
above).  It  allows to use a faster scaling algorithm for thumbnails creation
(but the reduction quality will be lower).


    @{b}Minimize requesters :@{ub}

Allows to skip the most trivial requesters (like "Are you sure  you  want  to
quit ?", and other messages that are not so important).


    @{b}Auto unselect :@{ub}

Allows to unselect thumbnails automatically after they've been processed. For
example,  if  you  select  some  thumbnails,  and  call  the  "View selected"
function, these thumbnails will be automatically unselected when the  viewing
operation is finished...


    @{b}Disable popup :@{ub}

Allows to disable the popup menu that appears when pressing the  right  mouse
button over a thumbnail.


    @{b}XPK Compression :@{ub}

Allows to activate XPK compression. You'll then be able to save your  indexes
into  a  compacted  format  which  will take less room on your disk. For this
option to be available, you must  have  installed  the  XpkMaster.library  in
LIBS:,  and  some  compression  libraries  (NUKE,  MASH,  SHRI  or others) in
LIBS:Compressors...


    @{b}Screen mode :@{ub}

Allows to choose the resolution that the  Collector  screen  will  use.  This
screen can't be smaller than 640 * 256 pixels...


    @{b}Thumbnails size :@{ub}

Allows to define the size of the generated thumbnails. You can choose  80x80,
96x96, 112x112, 128x128 pixels, or any other size (but the width must be a 16
multiple)... You must keep in mind that the larger the  thumbnails  are,  the
bigger the indexes will be in memory and on disk...


    @{b}Thumbnails colors :@{ub}

Allows to define the number of colors used by the thumbnails. You can  choose
16 or 256 grayscales or 256 colors.

If you choose a grayscale  display,  I  suggest  you  choose  16  grayscales,
because  the  difference  with  the 256 grayscales is really minimal, and the
thumbnails occupy twice less room in 16 grayscales than in 256.


    @{b}Thumbnails font :@{ub}

Allows to define the font used for displaying the names under the thumbnails.
The Collector interface will adapt automatically to all the font types (fixed
or proportional sizes, even vector compugraphic fonts are OK).


    @{b}Maximum number of thumbnails :@{ub}

Defines the maximum number of thumbnails that an index  can  contain.  Useful
for creating an index into several volumes, thus allowing to save memory with
indexes that would be too large (see @{"Add" link Add}).


    @{b}Exclude pattern :@{ub}

You can define a pattern for automatically exclude  certain  file  names.  So
everytime  you'll  enter  a  pattern  into  the  string  gadget  of  the file
requester, and a file list will be computed by Collector, the exclude pattern
will also be used. It's particularly useful for automatic completion, because
it allows to avoid completion with certain files : for example, enter #?.info
as the exclude pattern to automatically ignore icon files.


    @{b}Exported panels size :@{ub}

Allows you to define the width and the height of the graphic panels when  you
use  "Export  selected  as  panels"  to  export your index into a displayable
format...


    @{b}JPEG Quality :@{ub}

Allows to define the quality of the JPEG pictures created by Collector.  This
value  ranges  from  0  (low  quality / small file) to 100 (highest quality /
biggest file).


    @{b}HTML Format :@{ub}

Allows to define how many columns and rows  HTML  tables  will  contain  when
eporting HTML pages.


    @{b}Sort method :@{ub}

Allows you to define the sort criterion used when sorting your index. If  the
method  is  set  to "None", a requester will appear when you select "Sort" in
the "Thumbnail" menu and propose you to select the sort method "on the  fly".
Note  that when you use the "Update index files", the indexes won't be sorted
if the method is set to "None".


    @{b}Load settings :@{ub}

Restores the last saved preferences...


    @{b}Save settings :@{ub}

Saves the current preferences. Note that  the  current  paths  for  accessing
indexes  and  pictures  will  be  saved  too... You can then define a default
directory for your indexes and your pictures by going  to  the  corresponding
directories and then by saving the preferences...

@endnode

@node Hints "Hints and tips"

@{b}Questions and answers about Collector :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

@{b}Q : How do I convert indexes created with Collector 1.x into 2.x format ?@{ub}
A : It's really simple with the supplied converter (called "IndexConv") !  In
the shell, simply type "IndexConv <old_index> <new_index>".

So if you want to convert the index called "Test.Idx" into  an  index  called
"Test_New.Idx", just type in the shell :

                        "IndexConv Test.Idx Test_New.Idx".

That's all.

NOTE : The converter needs the AMOS.Library to run, but if you need to use it,
you certainly already have it... ;-)


@{b}Q : Creation of thumbnails can be slow... Is there a way to accelerate it ?@{ub}
A : Collector (in fact the MPimage.library) uses the datatypes  to  load  the
pictures.  It  can be slow since it loads the entire picture (it can't do any
"on the fly" scaling operation), before reducing it. But on the  other  hand,
the  datatypes  system offer great flexibility : you can archive any file you
want, provided you have the datatype for it (you can archive your fonts  with
the font.datatype, for example !).

But there's still a way to REALLY speed up  the  creation  of  JPEG  pictures
thumbnails : indeed, the MPimage.library, if correctly configured, can use an
external program called djpeg for JPEG decoding. And this program allows  "on
the  fly"  scaling, speeding up the whole process tremendously (JPEG pictures
are added almost instantaneously !).
(The same idea can be used for PNG pictures, with the program PNGTOPNM).

However, the correct installation of the djpeg program  and  the  environment
variables  needed to make it work with Collector is a bit tedious. That's why
I made small archives, with an installer script to  make  your  life  easier.
Moreover,  you'll find compiled versions of djpeg for all the processors ! So
to get these archives, just visit  the  Collector  support  home  page  (many
thanks  to  Gérard  Cornu  for  his  help  !  ;-)), and get the djpeg archive
corresponding to your CPU. Then use the provided install script, and all will
be fine !! The Collector support page can be found at :

    http://www.dtr.fr/homepage/gcornu/collector.html (<- case sensitive !!)


@{b}Q : Some thumbnails are only black boxes (especially with JPEG pictures).
What is the problem ?@{ub}
A : It may come from your datatypes. Some people reported problems  with  bad
coded  JPEG datatypes. I recommend the use of the JFIF datatype or the akJFIF
datatype, which  seem  to  work  correctly  (both  available  on  Aminet,  in
util/dtype).
For those who use the latest picture datatype v43  from  Ralph  Schmidt,  you
must  use  the  MPImage library v8.2 and above (provided with Collector), and
everything should work fine...


@{b}Q : When I use the complete function, some thumbnails that are already in my
index are added again. Why ? @{ub}
A : Use the "Update Index" operation on your index, then try again.  Normally
all  should  be  fine  (this  problem  only  occurs  with  early  versions of
Collector).

@{b}Q : Can I change the screen colors ?@{ub}
A : Yes ! If you're not totally satisfied with the screen colors, you  should
know  that Collector adjusts its screen palette from the palettes files found
in the "Palettes" directory. So you can edit them with your  favourite  paint
program,  and  Collector  will  then  adapt  its  colors to your new palette.
WARNING ! The palette file (which is an ILBM file) must contain a BODY  chunk
! As you can see it, this operation is reserved to expert users and shouldn't
be needed anyway (just for those who are never happy ;-)).

@endnode


@node Future "The future of Collector"

@{b}The future of Collector :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Okay, Collector 3.5 seems now quite powerful and stable, and I don't have  so
much time to work on it.

Then I won't add many  more  features  to  Collector.  Anyway  the  Collector
project  is  absolutely  not  dead  ! I'll still fix bugs (and even make some
minor improvements to it).

So don't hesitate to contact me about Collector if you have trouble with  it,
I'll always be happy to support this program ! (see @{"Author" link Author}).

@endnode

@node Bugs "Bugs / Limitations"

@{b}Known bugs :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~
Collector has been  tested  with  Enforcer,  which  guarantees  legal  memory
accesses.

All the functions have been thoroughly tested and seem to work correctly.

However, we're not protected against a hidden bug... :-(

That's why if you find one of these nasty bugs, I would be really grateful if
you send me a little mail and tell me how to reproduce it. Thanks...


@{b}Limitations :@{ub}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~
If you define a height for your thumbnails that is greater than the height of
your  display,  the  thumbnails  won't  be able to fit in the screen and will
overlay the control panel. Not really dangerous, but of course you may not be
able  to  see  your  indexes correctly. The only solution is simply to change
your screen resolution to a higher one, or reduce the size of your thumbnails
(the  second  solution is better, since smaller thumbnails will make you save
memory and disk space, with minimal quality loss).

@endnode

